{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_junco_ver01/data/sn83045499/00514154430/1948110901/0842.xml":{"full_text":"Daily Alaska Empire\n\u25a0Mbllshed every evening except Sunday by the\n.\"MPlftE PWVTING COMPANY\nSecond and Mo in Streets, Juneau, Alaska\nEKLEN THO^ MON&CN President\ni^OROTHY TROY LINGO Vice-President\nYILLIAkf R CARTER Editor and Manager\nELMER A. FRIEND Managing Editor\n1LPRKD ZENO HR Bu^lnea* Manager\nto.u-r.-d in the Post Office in Juneau as Second Class Matter\nSUBSCRIPTION BATES:\n\u2014Itvertd tr carrier in Juncao and Doarlas far 51.M ear aaoath\nsix months. Ik.Wii one year, I15.ee\nBy mall, postage raid, at the following rates:\nOne year. In advance. 116.00; six months, in advance, 17.50,\n\u00abw month. In advance. 11.50.\nSubscribers 1L confer a fever If they will promptly notify\nBusiness Office of any, failure os Irregularity In tha delivery\n\u20224 the\u00bb\u00bb papers.\nTelephones: New* Office. 602: Business Office. 374.\nMEMBER Of ASSOCIATED PRESS\nTn AaaocteUd Prc *6 is exclusively entitled to the jne tor\nM.\u2019mtllration of all news dlsps'cnes credited to It or not ether\nvise credited in tals paper tfnd also the local news published\nlereln.\nrational REPRESENTATIVES Alaska Newspapers. 71411\nw,urth Avenue Bldg Seattle, Wasiv.\nDIVORCE RECESSION\nA national sigh of relief has followed the report\nthat the divorce boom is in recession. Perhaps we\nare not headed toward Sodom and Gomorrah, after\nall, or even toward one divorce to every two mar\nriages, as was widely predicted two years ago when\nthe rate approached a l-to-3 ratio. Though it is still\nwell above that of the prewar period, its steady\ndrop across the country through 1947 and on into 1948\nshows that at least the marital mistakes of war have\nbeen straightened out to a large degree. Whether\nit shows a trend toward stabler marriage is debatable.\nFor it is likely that the high cost of living has hurt\nthe divorce business. The recession in that business\nfirst showed up at Reno about the timet* luxury goods\nbegan their decline. The drop has now spread to those\ngroups that cannot afford Reno divorces. Also, divorce\nstatistics may be affected by an increase in \"poor\nman's divorce\u201d\u2014desertion\u2014which tends to soar when\nthe pinch of living is felt.\nHowever, since prosperity is still general among\nmany groups of the population\u2014and divorce normal\nly is high in such periods\u2014there is a chance its reces\nsion may mean that a settling-down rnood is mani\nfesting itself in family life, perhaps as part of the\nsocial and political conservatism of the day. And while\nthe long-term divorce trend has been upward through\nthis century at least, many social scientists see hope\nthat it will lower or at least stabilize as a result of the\nwidespread education for marriage and training in\nhuman relations now being sponsored by churches,\nschools, colleges and communities. As human beings\nget to understand and manage themselves better, fam\nily life ought to become stabler and happier.\n\u201cPeople are losing their fear of hell,\u201d asserts an\nevangelist, Well, no wonder\u2014it is said that familiarity'\nbreeds contempt.\nNo matter what the occasion, a woman invariably\nanswers questions as if she were being cross-examined, y\nrhe Washington\nMerry-Go-Round\nBy DREW PEARSON\nContinued from Page One)\nsides I tried to call the shots all\nduring the campaign. I said a lot\nof nice things about the President.\nI was about the only one who de\nfended his idea of sending Chief\nJustice Vinson to Moscow. I com\npared his courageous war record\nwith Dewey's farm draft deferment.\nI told about his devout desire for\npeace and his reluctance to drop\nthe atomic bomb. I defended him\non a whole raft of things. But\n'Yes, I know your alibi.\" says\nthe wife, not even willing to let\nme finish what I was going to say.\n\u2018The Republican editors cut alj\nthe nice things you said out of the\ncolumn. So whgt? Then say them\non the radio where you aren\u2019t\ncensored.\n\"I want you to come out on the\nradio,\u2019\u2019 she demands, \"and give\nHarry a great big hand. You're\nchairman ol Be Kind To Pussy\nWeek' why don't you start a 'Be\nKind To Harry Week\"?\"\n\u2022'Incidentally, you\u2019realways go-i\ning in for Democratic contests\nand slogans,\" continues Mrs. P .wlio\nis now really steamed up. \u201cI\u2019ll give\nyou a slogan free. You won\u2019t have\nto pay me $20,000 in prizes. Here\nit is: \u2018Don't Hamper Harry, Help\nHim.\u2019\nMESSAGE TO TROIAN\nWell, that ended that. However,\nMrs. P, who ha^ good sense about\nmost things (except pigs', hit the\nnail right on 'he head.\nIt was a great victory, in a sense\ngreater than Roosevelt's victories\nbecause Truman fought it single\nhanded. with a divided party, and\nwith an extra quota of nonpayiiig\ndeadheads dragging their feet on\nhis bandwagon.\nSo. to the President of the United\nStates I would like to say:\n\"Although I was wrong in pre\ndicting your defeat, I am glad I\nwas wrong. And after that grand\nfight you put up, and regardless\nof any names you may have called\nme. I don't know anyone I would\nrather eat humble pie for than a\ngood sport and a great battler\nlike you.\n\"You, Mr. President, now have\nyour own mandate from the people.\nWo expect a new low in general despondency\nto be reached when soap opera goes to television.\nIt isn't, fair to hold a man accountable for any\ni thing he says under the influence of fear, eloquence,\nliquor or woman.\n\u201cWoman Has Baby While Climbing Mountain.\u201d\u2014\nHeadline. Well, maybe so, but we'll bet it slowed her\ndown some.\nTo date, whenever the lion and lamb have lain\ndown together, the latter has been on the inside of\nthe former.\nHow to get rich: Earn considerably more money\nthan you need and save the difference for a number\nof years.\nIf you lean over backwards in being fair, it's\nharder for your enemies to kick you in the pants.\nWhy is it that easy money is go hard to save?\nRemarkable Men\n(Anchorage Newsi\nRecently a remarkable group of people celebrated\nthe first year of its existence in Anchorage. The\ngathering was the first annual meeting of the An\nchorage chapter of Alcoholics Anonymous, an unusual,\norganization which exists solely for the good it does\neach individual member. There are no dues, there\nare no rigid by-laws, there are no initiation cere\nmonies. There are a few simnle rules that each man\nmust abide by, the outstanding of which is a burn\ning and since deseire to stop drinking.\nThere are perhaps a score of members in the\nAnchorage group and they are a remarkable lot of\nmen. They range from former attorneys to miners\nand all at one time were afflicted with one of the\nsociety\u2019s most horrible but seemingly uncurable\ndiseases\u2014Alcoholism.\nThese men all of stalwart character suffered from\na susceptibility for alcohol that defied medical science.\nOnly by banding together and speaking frankly of their\nI malady and gaining confidence from fellow members\ncould they shake it off and become normal men again.\nThe other night the A. A. group of Anchorage\nbroke precedence by momentarily dropping their an\nonimity and inviting a few \u201coutside\u201d to their meeting.\nThe guests who were privilege to attend could not\nhelp but be installed with the deep faith of these\nmen in their knowledge that through helping others\nthey have helped themselves. Their testimonials,\ngiven voluntarily and freely revealed the tremendous\ngratitude for the opportunity af'orded each member\nin becoming associated with AA and shaking off his\nfearful malady. Only those who make the grade\nremain members of AA and it was a tribute to the\nlocal group\u2019s endeavor to learn that its membership\nis growing and not receding.\nMen at the meting told how they had been drunks\nfor 20 years, how they had gone on \"benders\u201d that\nlasted for as long as 18 months, how they had lost\ntheir families and friends. All this behind them now,\neach gave reverent thanks to Alcoholic Anonymous.\nSome statistics, nationally, indicate that the his\ntory of AA is everywhere the same as in Anchorage.\nIt was founded in 1934 by Bill W., an attorney. Five\nyears later AA had 100 members. On August 1 of this\nyear there were 67,850 members in all States, the\nTerritories and some foreign countries.\nThe small bands grow daily spreading their good\nwithout fanfare and without pay. They are doing a\nservice that medical men, psychologists and even\nchurchmen have failed in attempting. It is a shame\nthe Anchorage group cannot stand up and take a\npublic bow.\nThey are anxious however, to get in touch with\nthose needing AA\u2019s help. Summoning a member\n*is accomplished by dropping a card to AA, Box 55,\nmchorage. It is that simple.\nYou won it entirely on your own.\nYou need feel no inferiority com\nplex that you were a political ac\ncident who came into office\nthrough another man\u2019s choice.\n\u201cNor need you feel any obliga\ntion to some of the Cabinet Ju\ndases who buttered you up to your\nface, while making deals with the\nenemy behind your back; nor to\nothers in your official family who\ndon\u2019t pull their full weight on the\noar. The people will applaud if\nyou get rid of them; if you banish\nentirely all Government-by-cron\niefc.\n\u201cThe Nation is expecting big\nthings oi you, Mr. President\nBig things in extremely trying\ntimes.\n\"For my part I would rather\nwrite the good than the bad. And\nthough I know you believe in fail\ncriticism, I for one would like to\nurge that we work, strive, give as\na united nation and \u2019help Harry,\nnot hamper him\u2019 to make demo\ncracy live.\u2019\u2019\nELECTION-WENT-ROUNI)\nFlushed friends of Harry Truman\nwere talking with him at Inde\npendence, Mo., regarding the chief\nfactor behind his victory. He said\nit was hard work. \"I grew up on\na farm where you have to work\nfor what you get.\" remarked the\nPresident While Truman's\n1 campaigning undoubtedly won him\nvotes, Wallace\u2019s didn\u2019t. Here are\nthe tell-tale figure; of Wallace's\n986.771 votes. 844.189 came from\neight states. The rest of the coun\ntry where he gathered crowds just\ndidn\u2019t vote for him. In other\nwords. 40 states were not affected\nby his trips or his radio broadcasts\nThe only three Cabinet mem\nbers who really worked for the re\nelection of their chief were Attor\nney General Tom Clark. Secretary\nof Agriculture Charlie Brannan\nand Secretary of Labor Maurice\nTobin. They rolled up their\nsleeves New Speaker Sam Ray\nburn has grave doubts as to wheth\ner the new Congress will tolerate\nCongressman J. \"Kickback\" Thom\nas, regardless of whether he is\nconvicted for taking salary kick\nbacks from clerks and stenograph\ners Republican Governor Kim\nSigler of Michigan was defeated\nby a young protege of Justice\nFrank Murphy\u2014Mennen Williams.\nWilliams, whose grandfather found\ned the Williams soap and Menncn's\nbaby-powder business, came to\nWashington as aide to Murphy\nwhen he was Attorney General\nWatch Williams. You can figure\non Williams challenging the seat\nof Senator Homer Ferguson the\nnext time around The man\nwho swung last-minute votes\nagainst Sigler was Mayor George\nWelch of Grand Rapids, president\nof the Mayors Conference of Amer\nica. He whaled thousands of votes\naway from Sigler by telling Mich\niganders how Sigler knifed the\nplan to rebate part of the sales\ntax to Michigan schools and cities\nShrewdest move Truman made\n,n the entire campaign was recon\nvening the 80th Congress right\nafter the Philadelphia convention\nin July. When the Republicans ad-\njourned without acting on infla\ntion, price control, housing or\nteachers\u2019 pay, etc., it clinched more\nvotes than any other campaign\nissues It was Col. Jake Ar- 1\nvey. Democratic boss of Chicago,\nvigorous opponent of Truman's\nnomination at Philadelphia, who\ngot out the biggest crowd for him\nof the entire campaign.\nNOVEMBER 9\nCharles J. Jenne\nI. M. Johnson\nRodney Noidling\nDean Williams\nAlfred Brown\nReggie Kleweno\nBetty Kelsey\nMrs. Ray Graham\nMANY BRAVE STORM\nTO ATTEND BACK\nTO SCHOOL NIGHT\nOver one hundred people braved I\nthe autumn storms last night to be'\npresent at the Back to School night I\nwhich was held in the Juneau\nSchools between the hours of seven I\n'and nine. i\nAll the classrooms in the Grade\nSchool were gaily decorated with\nart work made by the pupils. On\neach desk were workbooks and sam-1\npies ol the children's school work.\nThe Grade School .gymnasium is\nbeing used as a k.ndergarten class- J\nrocm. The walls of the gymnasium\nire colorfully decorated with large\nposters of story book characters,\nw ich were originally used for deco\nrations at the Publications Hop.\nOn the second floor of the High\nSchool was a display of classroom\npictures' of all students In the Grade\nchool. Teachers were present in all\nthe rooms to meet the parents and\nu the progress of the students.\nA short mus.cal program was pre\n-ented at 8:30 o\u2019clock in the Grade\nSchool Auditorium. The augmented j\n;ne..u High School Band played\nlour selections. The first selection,\nShow Boy\" was directed by Toby\nDunlap, student director oi the\nband. Joseph Shofner, director of\nthe music department, led the band\nin \u2018Bells Across the Meadows,\"\n\u201cSeeds of Cadmus,\u201d \"Bells of St.\nMary's.\u201d As its concluding number,\nthe band played \u201cScarlet and\nBlack,\" the Juneau High School\nsong, a peppy snap.\nThere are 40 grade school and\nhigh school students in the band j\nand there are 80 students enrolled:\nin the instrumental music course.\nThe Mixed Chorus of the High\nSchool presented two songs, \"Come.\nto the Pair,\u201d and \u201cIf You V/ere the J\nOnly Girl in the World.\u201d Miss Beat- j\nrice McNeeley is director of the I\nChorus. The Girls\u2019 Chorus sang j\n\"Tea for Two.\" Miss Ann Henning\nwas accompanist for the songs.\nThere are 39 girls in the group and\n18 boys, and this program was one i\nof the best presented in years be- j\ncause of the popular swing.\nParents who assisted the grade!\nschool teachers in their hostessing j\nduties were Mesdames Ralph Mize, I\nJ. Madsen. Cecil CaSler, J. McNa-1\nmara, Steve Sheldon, Jr., Harold\nSnaring, David Ramsay, Monte\nGrisham. Harold Foss, A. Walker,\nGeorge Clark, Zalmain Gross, Dewey\nBaker, T, J. Pyle, Vance Blackwell,\nStanley Grummett, Dan Livie, Sev\nern Swanson, G. Jensen, and Dr.\nW. P. Blaton.\nCONCERT BAND WILL\nPRACTICE TONIGHT\nAT 7:30 O'CLOCK\nJuneau\u2019s concert band will re\nhearse at 7:30 o'clock tonight in\nthe Grade School auditorium. The\nentile program to be given at the\n20th Century Theatre on Novem\nber 23 will be in practice and all\nband members are urged to be on\nI time at the advanced hour.\n^Crosswor^Puzzle\nACROSS\n1. Calls at brldg*\n5. Warbled\n9. Draw\n12. Mine entrance\n13. Always\n14. Pulpy fruit\nlo. Amount of\nmedicine\n16. Replenished\n18. Thin metal\ndisk\n20. Dens\n21. Pointer on a\nsu ndial\n23. Shears\n2<t. Red\n25. Troubled\n27. Pronoun\n29. Hail and\nfarewell\n30. Icelandic tales\n31. b; possible\n32. Two: prefix\n33. Regions\n34. Operatic\nheroine\n35. New Zealand\ntimber tree*\n37. Our sole\nconnection\nwith the\nouter world\n39. Trigonometri\ncal function*\n40. Baseball\nteams\n41. Common\nevery wher*\n43. Cover the\ninside\n46. Devoured\n47. Genus of the\nrose 51\n4S. Smooth\n49. King: Latin\n50. Set out on a\nvoyage\n1\nIa|s|t|r|a|y|\nTsl\n(HEEDED\n\u25a1EC QEOE\n\nT O S\nI\nCOCO\nmi\n\u25a1\u25a1DC\nmSsnauMM\nBEE\nSolution of Yesterday\u2019s Puzzle\nGarden\nnecessity\nDOWN\nPoor\n2. Artificial\nlanguage\n3. Arrange\n4. Vaporous\n5. Musical salutes\n6. Biblical city\n7. Clock in the\nform of a\nship\n8. Gratings of\nwrought\nIron\n3. Flower\n10. Darken\n11. Stuffs\n17. Deposited\n10. Toward\n21. Seize\n22. Period of\nprobation\n23. Of the highest\nrank of\nliterature\nand art\n26. Mount aw In\nAsia Minor\n28. Unfledged bird\n30. Rubbers\n31. Letter\n33. Impressed with\nsolemn\nwonder\n34. Anoints\n36. Add\n3s. Type measure\n20. Box\n40. Unless: Latin\n42. Extinct New\nZealand bird\n44. By birth\n4*. Finish\nf\n20 YEARS AGO ^iTe empire\nNOVEMBER 9. 1928\nCapt. and Mrs. E. K. Tobin of the Salvation Army, returned from\nKetchikan where they had been attending the Native Congress.\nAn Armistice Day dance was to be given by the American Legion\nat the A. B. Hall on November 10. The celebration was to mark the\n10th anniversary of the American Legion. There were to be special\nmusical features, beautiful decorations, and unique entertainment ac\ncording to L. Keen of the dance committee. The drum corps was to sfart\noff the evening's entertainment.\nMrs. Lena Perelle, who had been receiving medical treatment for\na week, was discharged from St. Ann\u2019s Hospital and returned to her\nhome.\nJ. W. McCord, President of the Kodiak Livestock Association, was\nvisiting in Juneau for several days. He owned a cattle ranch on Sitkalidak\nisland.\nHarry Sperling, District Deputy Grand Exalted Ruler, B. P. O.\nElks, left for Anchorage and Cordova to pay an official visit to the\nlodges there.\nIke P. Taylor wa^ appointed to be the official representative of\nAlaska at the annual convention of the American Road Builders at1\nCleveland.\nWeather: High, 33: low, 32; clear.\nDaily Lessons in English w. l. Gordon\nWORDS OFTEN MISUSED: Do not say, \"A large per cent of\nthe profits go to charity.\" Say, \u201cA large PERCENTAGE of the profits\nGOES to charity.\u201d\nOFTEN MISPRONOUNCED: Licorice. Pronounce lik-o-ris, both\nIT's as in IT, O as in NO, and not lik-o-rish.\nOFTEN MISSPELLED: Assent (consenti. Ascent (a rise). Accent]\n(a stress).\nSYNONYMS: Sympathy, commiseration, compassion, condolence,1\ntenderness.\nWORD STUDY: \u201cUse a word three times and it is yours.\" Let us\nincrease our vocabulary by mastering one word each day. Today's word:\nREGENERATE (verb); to reform completely. \u201cOne great thought breath\ned into man may regenerate him.\"\u2014Channing.\nMODERN ETIQUETTE' Xehta i.7e\nQ. Is there a certain order in which automobiles leave, following\na church wedding?\nA. Yes. The cat of the bride and bridegroom leaves first, then\nthe bridesmaids, followed by the bride\u2019s parents, then the bridegroom\u2019s\nparents, next the nearest relatives, last the friends.\nQ. Is it rude for a guest at dinner to refuse a dish?\nA. At a small dinner, where the hostess may not have a large\nvariety of dishes, it is better to partake of each, even if all of It is not\neaten.\nQ. Should one cut buttered potatoes with the knife?\nA. No; only the fork should be used.\nLOOK and LEARN hz c. GORDON\n1. What is the distance of the horizon when standing on the shore?\n2. Which are the seven most valuable furs?\n3. Who was the only President of the United States who had no\nformal schooling?\n4. Where is the baseball Hall of Fame?\n5. Which animal lives to the greatest age?\nANSWERS:\n1. At eye level, on the surface of the sea, the range of vision is\nonly a little less than three miles.\n2. Seal, otter, beaver, sable, marten, mink, and fox.\n3. Andrew Johnson. Two-thirds of the Presidents have been col\nlege graduates.\n4. Cooperstown, N. Y.\n5. The elephant.\nPlumbing Heating\nOil Burners\nTelephone 319 Nighis-Red 730\nHarri Machine Shop9 tnc.\nOldest Bank in Alaska\n1891\u2014Over Half a Century of Banking\u20141948\nThe B. ML Behrends\nBank\nSafety Deposit\nBoxes for Rent\nCOMMERCIAL SAVINGS\nNELS LEE\nas a paid-up subscriber to THE DAILY ALASKA\nEMPIRE is invited to be our guest Tills EVENING\nPresent this coupon to the box office of the\nCAPITOL THEATRE\nand receive TWO TICKETS to see:\n\"TO THE ENDS OF THE EARTH\"\nFederal Tax\u201412c\u2014Paid by the Theatre\nPHONE 14\u2014THE ROYAL RLUE CAR CO.\nand an insured cab WILL CALL FOR YOU and\nRETURN YOU to your home with our compliments.\nWATCH THIS SPACE\u2014Your Nam